Both outputs are written. Summary of what I did:

- Ran 15 iterations of propose-test-refine on the 50,000-patient prostate cohort.
- Found a dominant predictor: feature_078 (Spearman ρ=+0.85 with pfs_months, slope +0.174 mo/unit), plus log(feature_013) negative, feature_006 negative, feature_009 positive, feature_092 inverse-U, and protective binary markers feature_109/feature_039/feature_027.
- A 14-term parsimonious model with three feature_078 interactions and two quadratics reaches R²=0.826 — essentially saturating the explainable signal (full 122-feature OLS gets 0.823).
- The univariate feature_051 effect (-0.52 mo) is fully confounded by the four core continuous predictors.
- Race (feature_018) and insurance (feature_045) show no association with pfs_months at any level: marginal ANOVAs (p=0.69, 0.79), adjusted main effects (all p≥0.29), residual-mean ANOVAs (p=0.85, 0.73), and joint F-tests of every demographic × predictor interaction tested (all p≥0.22). The eight key predictors are balanced across both demographics.

Files emitted: `transcript.json` (schema-validated, 15 iterations / 39 hypotheses / 37 analyses) and `analysis_summary.txt`.
